NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now as to the play. This is a bit of an unusual hand in the sense that the dummy has the long trumps rather than declarer. In a sense, South is really the declarer, but that is hard for most people to visualize.|
PG| ***** 85 ***** |


AT|
dee_dee_20: Do you call this set up  dummy reversal?|
PG| ***** 86 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Good question Dee. Not exactly. A dummy reversal works as follows. Suppose you have 5 trumps in declarer's hand, and say 4 in dummy. In a dummy reversal, you might ruff 3 or more times in the hand with 5 trumps which is declarer's hand. Typically, you try and make extra tricks by ruffing in dummy. But if you try and make extra tricks by ruffing with declarer, that is a dummy reversal. But that assumes declarer is the one with long trumps. In this case dummy is the one with long trumps. Anyway, back to the play. There is no reason for Roberta to ruff spades. |
PG| ***** 87 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|All that does is shorten her trumps and it does not result in any extra tricks. In general, you should avoid deliberately making the long hand ruff, unless you need entries. What she should do is draw trumps and work on the red suits. In hearts, she should hope Dee has at least one heart honor, and lead low towards the Queen-Jack twice. If Dee has at least one heart honor, then Roberta will score one heart trick. |
PG| ***** 88 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And in diamonds she should do 2 things.
a) Play towards the King, in the unlikely event (due to the auction) that Patti has the Ace and 
b) Preserve a trump to ruff the third diamond.

So, her best plan is to win the Ace of spades and lead a heart only because they were 2-2. Eventually get to dummy, and lead a diamond towards the King. Don't draw trumps until 2 rounds of diamonds are played.|
