qx|B03, To Bid or Not To Bid Game|ht|d|CS|2|AT|^-

{Determining If You Should Bid Game}
 
As opening bidder, your hand falls in one of three categories:
 - minimum (13-15 points)
- medium (16-18 points)
- maximum (19+ points) 
|
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


AT|
The above ranges in part are based on Bergen's hand evaluation method which Howard feels comfortable with them. |
PG| ***** 135 ***** |


AT|

However, the following are Bergen's ranges.
 - minimum (13-16 points)
- medium (17-19 points)
- maximum (20+ points) |
PG| ***** 136 ***** |


AT|

Similarly, as responder, your hand falls in one of three categories:
  - minimum (6-9 points)
  - medium (10-12 points)
  - maximum (12+ points)|
PG| ***** 137 ***** |


AT|

Remember, game requires that the combined partnership assets be at least 26 points.

The following table summarizes how the partnership can tell 
whether or not they have enough points to bid game:|
PG| ***** 138 ***** |


NT||ht|d|at|

^hOpener
^BResponder           ^EMinimum  ^HMedium  ^KMaximum
^BMinimum             ^E No      ^H No     ^K Yes
^BMedium              ^E No      ^H Yes    ^K Yes
^BMaximum             ^E Yes     ^H Yes    ^K Yes|
PG| ***** 139 ***** |


AT|

^-During the auction, both partners should always be thinking about whether it is still possible to bid game. 
For example, if your partner opens and you, as responder, have a maximum (12+) hand, you should bid game. 
Similarly, if you open with a maximum (19+) and get any response from partner, you should bid game.
^-|
PG| ***** 140 ***** |


at|
^-
{The Captain}

(We men, in particular, should pay special attention to this section because we will find it emotionally difficult to follow 
these principles!) Although the bidding is a cooperative effort, one of the partners is considered the 
"Captain" of the hand. The other partner is considered the subordinate (men, substitute "peon" or even "slave" so 
you get the point).|
PG| ***** 141 ***** |


AT|

The Captain is in charge of deciding the final contract. This is accomplished by asking the subordinate to further describe
his/her hand and, perhaps, giving a choice of contracts. The subordinate simply answers the Captain's questions. 
This next sentence is very important. 
On almost all hands, THE RESPONDER IS THE CAPTAIN OF THE HAND. So (men), once you open the hand, you are 
relegated to being the subordinate. Similarly (ladies), you as responder are the Captain and in charge of the auction.|CS|2|
PG| ***** 142 ***** |


nt||HT|D|AT|^-

{The Captain's Tools}

The main difficulty for the Captain is to communicate to the subordinate when to keep bidding and when to stop. The
main tool to accomplish this is the "New-Suit-Forcing" principle. If the responder bids a new suit, the opener is obligated to 
make another bid. Opener, if your partner introduces a new suit,|CP|8|AT| YOU MAY NOT PASS.|CP||
PG| ***** 143 ***** |


AT| 

{Some advanced partnerships even play a convention called "Fourth Suit Forcing." If 3 suits have been bid, 
and responder bids the fourth suit, which may be artificial, the partnership is committed to bid game}.|
PG| ***** 144 ***** |


AT|


The other forcing bid is for responder to jump (e.g. 1@H-1@S-2@C-3@S). This should be avoided, if possible, in favor of 
New Suit forcing, which leaves more room for further bidding.|
pg| ***** 145 ***** |


NT||qx||HT|D|CS|2|AT|^-

{The Subordinate's Tools}

The subordinate is responsible for describing both the strength
(e.g. minimum, medium, maximum) and suits in his/her hand. In this lesson,
we will concentrate on how to describe strength.

|
PG| ***** 146 ***** |


FP|2|CP|8|AT|Minimum |CP||fp||AT|hands are described by making the cheapest bid possible in the strain
opener wishes to bid.  

|
PG| ***** 147 ***** |


fp|2|CP|8|AT|Medium |CP||FP||AT|hands are a bit harder to describe. Fortunately, many medium
hands are opened 1NT. Another method is to jump in the opening suit.

|
PG| ***** 148 ***** |


fp|2|CP|8|AT|Maximum |CP||FP||AT|hands are described by jump shifting, 
bidding one level higher than necessary in a new suit.  |
PG| ***** 149 ***** |


at|

Another method to show a good medium (a good 17+ points) or maximum opening hand is to use a reverse. |
PG| ***** 150 ***** |


at|

Opener should avoid being redundant. Every new bid should provide
partner with new information. |
PG| ***** 151 ***** |


AT|

Rebidding your suit should promise a six-card suit. |
PG| ***** 152 ***** |


AT|

If you only have a five-card suit, bid another suit or bid NT.
^-|
